      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a classic sign of **nutrient deficiency**, specifically nitrogen, which is often the first thing the older, bottom leaves sacrifice to keep the new growth alive. It's a very common issue, especially if you've been over-fertilizing recently or if the soil pH is off, but don't worry, it's easily fixable!\n\nTo fix the soil, you should first test the pH level; if it's too acidic, add some lime, or if it's too alkaline, add some sulfur. You can also try adding a balanced organic fertilizer or compost to replenish the nutrients.\n\nWhile you're working on the soil, you might want to consider adding some **garden soil** to improve drainage, as compacted soil can prevent roots from getting the nutrients they need. Just remember, when you add new soil, make sure to mix it in gently so you don't disturb the root system too much.\n\nIf the yellowing persists after a few weeks, it could be a sign of **root rot** caused by overwatering, so check if the soil is staying too wet. In that case, you might need to repot the plant into a larger container with better drainage holes.\n\nSpeaking of drainage",
      "source": "target",
